@node Installation "DigiCam: Installation"

                                  Installation
                                 --------------

- copy DigiCam anywhere in your path

- copy DigiCam.guide wherever you can retrieve it.

- I suggest adding an alias to your s:shell-startup, just to avoid typing to
  much, e.g. 'alias dc DigiCam DEVICE serial.device UNIT 0 BPS 19200'

- 'DigiCam serial.device 0 19200 info' should list some information about your
   camera.

- 'DigiCam serial.device 0 19200 dir' should show a list of all picture.

- 'DigiCam serial.device 0 19200 GF=ALL filename' should download all pictures,
  if not you really have to read the manual.

- Download failed? Please take a look in the @{" camera directory " link DirectoriesO} section.

- Everything working? Try higher speed.
@endnode


@node Usage "DigiCam: Usage"

                                     Usage
                                    -------

      @{" General Options   " link GeneralO}
      @{" Downloading       " link DownloadingO}
      @{" Uploading         " link UploadingO}
      @{" Erasing           " link ErasingO}
      @{" Actions           " link ActionsO}
      @{" Settings          " link SettingsO}
      @{" Special Functions " link SpecialsO}

      @{" Using Directories " link DirectoriesO}   for DCF compliant cameras

   @{b}Please read the text below at first:@{ub}

   What I want to give you here is a brief description affecting all options.
   In advance, DigiCam is dumb but flexible :)

   Every setting of the camera e.g. resolution, are as numbers. The
   numbers are directly send to the camera. There is no interpretation done,
   so if you want a particular resolution you can't say: I want 'HI', you 
   have to say: I want '5' (or whatever). The representation of the numbers
   seems to vary much between the different cameras. At least the Sanyo
   VPC-X350EX differs from the protocol description in some points.

   To understand every option, you really should get the protocol-description
   from Eugene Crosser: http://www.average.org/digicam/protocol.html

   The always needed basics: DEVICE UNIT BPS
   e.g. DigiCam serial.device 0 230400

   DigiCam should supports any serial-driver, was tested on Amiga's internal
   serial port and a MultiFaceIII.

   Settings the BPS to 230400 is not a joke. The maximum speed for the Sanyo is
   230400 and my Amiga (Cyberstorm MK1 060/50MHz) managed it well to get that
   rate at his internal port using the standard serial.device as well as
   8n1.device or artser.device. It is true that the communication is only
   errorfree if I let my Amiga completely alone during transfers. But since
   errors are detected and damaged packets are rerequested by the camera,
   using 230400 with some resends is possible and still much faster than 115200.
   Upload of pictures is free of errors at this interface speed, but not using
   the full bandwith.

   DigiCam supports upto 921600, untested.

   In cases DigiCam seems to hang, wait some time because there should be a
   watchdog timeout everywhere. The longest timeout is cameradependent and takes
   45 secs on the Sanyo. To break the program via Ctrl-C is probably the faster
   solution then ...

   Commands can be nested but not repeated and are executed in a fixed order.
   1. all settings/registers are set, 2. info, 3. any eraseprocedure,
   4. takepicture/preview, 5. download
   e.g. DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 nametosave ERASEALL TP GF=1 DIR
@endnode

@node GeneralO "DigiCam: General Options"

                                General Options
                               -----------------

   INFO
   Writes some info about the camera, if some "denied by camera" are occuring
   don't be afraid.

   DIR
   Lists the pictures (and animations) stored in the camera, here you can also
   spy out the numbers matching the resolutions. Note: I found out, that not
   all models are showing the resolutions you can use to take a picture in the
   same format.
@endnode

@node DownloadingO "DigiCam: Downloading"
                                    
                                  Downloading
                                 -------------

   GF=GETFRAME       downloads picture(s), format: jpeg (EXIF, special format,
                     that includes more information about the picture. Some
                     datatypes won't display 'em). Can be also in TIFF
                     format for newer models. DigiCam will still save them with
                     suffix .jpg since no format exploration is done.
                     But you are using an Amiga, so why care for suffixes :)

   GT=GETFRAMETHUMB downloads the preview of a picture.

   GA=GETANIM        downloads anims, format: AVI/MOV, can be played by e.g.
                     CyberAVI/QT.
                     As for pictures, the format is not checked. Quicktimes are
                     also saved with the suffix .avi. The VPCSX500 records anims
                     as QT in M-JPEG. You definitely need a PowerPC to play them
                     at full speed.

   GAT=GETANIMTHUMB  downloads the preview of an anim.

   GU=GETAUDIO       downloads audiocomments from picture, format: WAV

   You can give a single one e.g. GF=11, ranges GF=1-10 and all, e.g. GF=All
   A filename is always needed, the filename is expanded with the type of the 
   download and the frame/animnumber.

   Download has a progress display, every dot represents a 2KB package, every
   exclamation mark a damaged, rerequested one.
@endnode

@node UploadingO "DigiCam: Uploading"

                                   Uploading
                                  -----------

   UP=UPLOAD
   Argument is a pattern or simply a single filename.
   E.g. UPLOAD=#?.jpg, UPLOAD=(1.jpg|2.jpg|3.jpg). Progress display while
   uploading is similar to downloading.

   If you want to upload a displayable picture, the picture needs to
   be the same type of jpeg as the camera uses. Since I don't know of any
   program on Amiga saving this type of jpeg, the only uploadable pictures
   are the pictures formerly downloaded from the camera.

   At least you can do a slideshow of your last holiday at your grandmas TV.

   The camera's behavoir when it should receive different kind of data is
   indistinct. The Sanyo VPC-SX500 accepts all kind of data. Everything can be
   uploaded. For unknown data a questionmark is shown at the LCD.

   I got the information that the Agfa ephoto 1280 crashes badly when it
   should receive any foreign kind of data.

@endnode

@node ErasingO "DigiCam: Erasing"

                                    Erasing
                                   ---------

   You can ERASEALL, ERASELAST or ERF=ERASEFRAME or ERA=ERASEANIM, single,
   range or all.

   Please note ERASEALL is not equal to ERASEFRAME=ALL, because ERASEALL is a
   single command and surely faster, but erases only pictures as well.
@endnode

@node ActionsO "DigiCam: Actions"

                                    Actions
                                   ---------

   TP=TAKEPICTURE  Takes a picture, just as pressing the release button.
                   DELAY can be used to set a delay in seconds for the
                   picture. The picture is stored in the camera.

   MP=MAKEPREVIEW  downloads a live-picture from the camera in a
                   fixed standardresolution.

   ST=SETTIME      Sets the cameratime to the current time of your Amiga.

   WC=WEBCAM       Webcam mode can be used to shot pictures in a sequence.
                   All will be saved with the same filename.
                   Argument is the approx. delay in seconds between single
                   shots.
                   To avoid problems with multiple tasks reading the file that
                   has to be written. Writing is done in a temporary file. The
                   file is renamed if done. If it fails because the target is
                   locked at the moment, DigiCam retries it upto 100 times.
                   If the file is still locked, DigiCam take a new picture and
                   the whole procedure is repeated.
                   Webcam mode starts with the deletion of all frames.

                   Attention: The constanly use of your digital camera is
                              nothing it is build for. Damage may occur. 
                              
                   To avoid stressing the memory card to much, the whole card
                   is filled with pictures. Therefore the card is erased at the
                   beginning of the session.
                   This is no joke, we actually did kill a smartmedia card with
                   shoting to much (very very much) pictures in first frame.

@endnode

@node SettingsO "DigiCam: Settings"


                                    Settings
                                   ----------

   All arguments are numbers, availability is modeldependent, some may be
   read-only (shown in INFO).

   All numbers and its representations are taken from the protocoldescription.
   It is always possible that there are different or more selections
   available.

   RES=RESOLUTION You should take picture in every resolution your camera is
                  capable of and spy the numbers out with DIR. Spying out
                  is not working for all models. You have to try then.

   SH=SHUTTERSPEED In microsecs.

   FM=FLASHMODE 0 Auto, 1 Force, 2 Off, 3 Anti RedEye, 4 SlowSync.

   AP=APERTURE 1 Low, 2 Mid, 3 Hi.

   CM=COLORMODE 1 Color, 2 B/W.

   LS=LCDSHUT Autoshuttime for the LCD in Secs.

   ASH=AUTOSHUTHOST Autoshuttime for camera if connected to a Computer
                    in secs.

   ASH=AUTOSHUTHOSTFIELD Autoshuttime for camera if single in secs.

   LM=LENSMODE 1 Macro, 2 Normal, 3 Infinity/Fisheye, e.g. read-only on
               the Sanyo, because the mode is mechanically switched.

   BM=BITMAP 1 AEL/WBL, 2 Fisheye, 4 Wide, 8 Digital Zoom, 16 B/W.

   EXP=EXPMETER 2 Center weighted, 3 Spot, 5 Multi element matrix.

   BC=BRIGTHNESSCONTR 0 Normal, 1 Bright+, 2 Bright-, 3 Contrast+,
                      4 Contrast-.

   WB=WHITEBALANCE 0 Auto, 1 Skylight, 2 Fluorescent, 3 Tungsten, 255 Cloudy.

   LD=LCDDATEFORMAT 1 YY/MM/DD, 2 DD/MM/HH, 3 DD/MM/YY

   LB=LCDBRIGHTNESS 1 to 7 maybe more
@endnode

@node SpecialsO "DigiCam: Special Functions"

                               Special Functions
                              -------------------

   These functions are to explore a camera, the search of new features.
   Note: Reading registers in a way there aren't meant may hang up the
         camera.
   Reading vdata-registers as int32-registers seems to be secure, if not
   done in to fast sequence.
   Reading int32-registers as vdata let the Sanyo hang up several time,
   using ranges while using READDATA is not safe.

   The Sanyo mostly resets itself after 45 seconds, but sometimes it is
   necessary to plug off the serial cable at the camera. Closing the shutter
   (switching it off) didn't help.


   RI=READINTREG single (RI=10) or range (RI=2-12). Tries to read the
                 registers as int32 and shows the result if possible.
                 Is intentionally slow for ranges, faster progress
                 worried the Sanyo.
                 Result is a number.

   RD=READDATA   single (RD=46) or range (RD=46-47). Tries to read the
                 registers as int32 and shows the result if possible.
                 Result is a hexdump and all readable characters.

   SI=SETINT     Allows you to set an int32-register with the value.
   V=VALUE       e.g. SI=7 V=0
                 Please be careful using this option, you never know
                 what can be screwed up by hitting unknown registers.

   TA=TAKEACTION Allows you to send an action command to the camera.
   V=VALUE       The argument send to the camera is value.
                 e.g. TA=2 V=0 takes a picture
@endnode

@node DirectoriesO "DigiCam: Special Directories"

                               Using Directories
                              -------------------

   There are two options to deal with camera internal directories:

   SFD=SCANFORDIRS    : scans the camera for directories
                        BUT: only picture directories can be found

   CD=CHANGEDIRECTORY : to change the directory
                        Directory have to be absolute, see Examples below

   DT=DIRTYPE         : to specify the directory type
                        picture, animation or audio=sound
                        Any unique abbreviation is ok. (p, a, s)

   Note: When using directories and types, GF=GETFRAMES can be always used
         for any type of data. DIR list the contents of the entered directory.
         Read the following section!

   @{b}Explanation@{ub}

   There is a group of newer cameras still using the same protocol but
   organizing the different types of recorded material in directories.
   Before it is possible to download, the correct directory has to be set.
   These cameras are DCF (Design rule for Camera Filesystem) compliant.

   Unluckily the directory structure is arbitrary and (as far as I could figure
   out) cannot completely be fetched from the camera. One simply have to know
   them. I hope that all cameras have a good manual that describes the directory
   structure as it might be interesting to all people using a card-adapter to
   read the memory card. At least the top directory is recommended to be /DCIM.

   Sanyo's VPC-SX500 manual gives the needed information. Its directory
   structure looks like this (the manual says ROOT for '/'):

   Dirname                   Contents                          Type

   /DCIM/100SANDS          : normal pictures in all formats    picture

   /DCIM/100SANDS/SEQT0001 : sequences of pictures that are    picture
                             taken in a special recording 
                             mode. Second sequence is in 
                             SEQT0002 and so on upto
                             SEQT0099.

   /DCIM/100SANDS/VCLP     : upto 999 animations               animation

   /DCIM/100SANDS/SUND     : upto 999 audio-only recordings    audio = sound

 
   If there are more anims/pics/audios than the numbers mentioned above, a new
   directory /DCIM/101SANDS is created. I could not try that out, because I only
   had a 8 MB compact flash card. Has anyone a spare IBM microdrive? Not?

   For the Sanyo, SFD=SCANFORDIRS can find the picture directories if the main
   directory is /DCIM. All other directories cannot be found by DigiCam.

   @{b}Download Examples@{ub}

   Examples for Sanyo's directory structure. Yours is probably different. RTM.

   Picture:
   DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 CD=/DCIM/100SANDS DT=P GF=All filename

   Picture Thumbnail:
   DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 CD=/DCIM/100SANDS DT=P GT=All filename

   Animation:
   DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 CD=/DCIM/100SANDS/VCLP DT=A GF=All filename

   Animation Thumbnail:
   DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 CD=/DCIM/100SANDS/VCLP DT=A GT=All filename

   Sound:
   DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 CD=/DCIM/100SANDS/SUND DT=S GF=All filename

   As shown above, when dealing with directories the normal GF=GETFRAMES is
   always used. There is no need to use the type-specific GETs as long as the
   directory type is correct.

   BUT:
   Sound comment from picture:
   DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 CD=/DCIM/100SANDS/ DT=P GU=All filename

   Some non-user @{" technical information. " link DirtechO}
@endnode

@node DirtechO "DigiCam: Technical Infos"

                                Technical Infos
                               -----------------

   Dirtype and Framenumbers

   Frames are requested by a 32-Bit number. The highest byte of this number
   specifies the type of the frame.

   Cameras without directories: 00 00 00 01 gets the first picture
                                FF 00 00 01 gets the first anim

   Ok, this kind of function sounds logical as long there is no other way to
   distinguish.

   But when using directories it seems not to be necessary anymore. However,
   at least the Sanyo still needs that kind of "number-typing" and there is
   a third one: F0 for soundfiles.

   If you use the DT=DIRTYPE option now, the highest byte of the framenumber is
   set according to the type: Pict=0x00, Anim=0xFF, Sound=0xF0.

   It is also possible to give directly the byte that should be used: e.g.
   DT=0x20, that may help if the future will bring cameras with a new type of
   frames. Where to get that number is a good question, answer for the really
   advanced (and sufficient equipped user) is the usage of seeserial (see
   goodies) directory.


   Directories

   seeserial can also be used to spy out the directory names. Please see goodies
   directory of installation archive. You need at least a computer running an
   original download software and an Amiga or Linux machine with two serial
   ports. Or a Macemulator and the Macversion of the download software and
   an Amiga with three serial ports .... maybe only one, if you can get
   nullser.device to do what it should do (it doesn't for me).
@endnode

